munity.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/56b4756feb3b30c1b570201c0e2216c4a05a6e1a.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f1036cc8393b3ef40451d45e9091fb9213bf92ce.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/754a0317c68293f33bf12e18ebae4de2b08f81b7.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/5954894f377de2935fd0505a2dfa91e1229e52cd.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/05bfab6050393e6c96f3a1bf8e5a5fcb099320ba.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/0160df6b10af9f47f73802569b3923b422f58dc3.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/ff0fc320b13a75505e6aa3cb9cccd5f49de22167.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/8/8f875f53214515cd7d91639a705e7a3967643aa7.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"/2X/4/46c96832a908906d90c9c301cd17c2888c2584a5.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a user interface from a Model Browser for an application labeled \u0022myapplication.\u0022 The navigation tree on the left displays the structure of various components, including \u0022Common,\u0022 \u0022Data,\u0022 \u0022Constants,\u0022 and \u0022Data Structures.\u0022 Under \u0022Data Structures,\u0022 subcategories are visible: \u0022__spreadsheet,\u0022 \u0022_system,\u0022 and \u0022Dimensions.\u0022 A context menu is shown, revealing options to create a \u0022New\u0022 item, with additional selections for \u0022Entity,\u0022 \u0022Filter Set,\u0022 \u0022New Group,\u0022 \u0022Repeat New\u0022 (F12), and \u0022Default Set.\u0022 The purpose of this interface appears to be for organizing and managing data structures within the application.\n\n\n  \n \n Name your Filter Set using the convention  Get  \u002B  FieldName  you want to refer to: \n \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/56b4756feb3b30c1b570201c0e2216c4a05a6e1a.png]\nDescription: The interface appears to be a configuration panel for a filter set named \u0022GetId.\u0022 It includes sections labeled \u0022(Info)\u0022 and \u0022(Schema Item)\u0022 with details regarding the filter\u0027s properties. Under \u0022(Info),\u0022 there are fields for \u0022Ancestors\u0022 marked as \u0022False,\u0022 \u0022Inheritable\u0022 also marked as \u0022False,\u0022 and \u0022Name\u0022 showing \u0022Get Id.\u0022 The \u0022Misc\u0022 section contains a field for \u0022IsDynamic,\u0022 which is marked as \u0022False.\u0022 This setup is likely used for defining or managing filter attributes within a software application or data service environment.\n\n\n  \n Save it. \n \n Right-click on the Filter Set you just created and choose  New  /  Filter . \n \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f1036cc8393b3ef40451d45e9091fb9213bf92ce.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a Model Browser interface for an application named \u0022myapplication.\u0022 The left panel features a hierarchical structure categorized under \u0022Common,\u0022 \u0022Data,\u0022 and \u0022Constants,\u0022 with a focus on \u0022Data Structures.\u0022 Under \u0022Data Structures,\u0022 there\u0027s a section labeled \u0022LookupPriority_Name_GetId\u0022 displaying \u0022Entities\u0022 and \u0022Filter Sets.\u0022 A dropdown menu is open, showing options including \u0022New,\u0022 \u0022New Group,\u0022 \u0022Repeat New F12,\u0022 and \u0022Actions,\u0022 with \u0022Filter\u0022 highlighted as the selected action. The purpose of this interface appears to be managing and organizing data structures within the application.\n\n\n  \n \n Fill in the following fields: \n \n \n  Entity : Select the entity you want to filter. \n  Filter : Choose the  GetId  filter. \n \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/754a0317c68293f33bf12e18ebae4de2b08f81b7.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for configuring a filter labeled \u0022Priority_GetId.\u0022 In the section titled \u0022(Info),\u0022 it shows \u0022Schema Item\u0022 with fields for \u0022Ancestors\u0022 (set to False), \u0022Inheritable\u0022 (set to False), and \u0022Name\u0022 (set to Priority_Get Id). The \u0022Condition\u0022 section includes parameters like \u0022IgnoreFilterConstant\u0022 and \u0022IgnoreFilterParameterName,\u0022 both set to False, along with \u0022PassWhenParameterMatch\u0022 also set to False. In the \u0022Misc\u0022 section, \u0022Entity\u0022 is noted as \u0022Priority\u0022 and \u0022Filter\u0022 as \u0022Get Id.\u0022 This interface is likely used for defining a data filtering criterion in a software application or database management system.\n\n\n  \n Save it. Notice that the filter name is automatically generated using our filter naming convention \u2013  Entity_Filter . \n   Lookup creation and setup \n Once you\u2019ve created the Data Structure and Filter, you can now create the Lookup. \n \n \n In the Model Browser, under your package, go to  Data  /  Lookups . \n \n \n Right-click on your application package folder and choose  New  /  Data Service Lookup : \n \n \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/5954894f377de2935fd0505a2dfa91e1229e52cd.png]\nDescription: The image displays the \u0022Model Browser\u0022 interface within a software application labeled \u0022myapplication.\u0022 The visible hierarchy includes sections such as \u0022Common,\u0022 \u0022Data,\u0022 and \u0022Lookups.\u0022 Under the \u0022Data\u0022 category, subcategories include \u0022Constants,\u0022 \u0022Data Structures,\u0022 \u0022Database Data Types,\u0022 \u0022Entities,\u0022 and \u0022Functions.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:46:03"},"vector":[-0.043980364,-0.032893512,-0.07797833,0.010679039,0.0018012613,-0.055304326,-0.016093582,0.01060477,0.0007474057,0.004655269,-0.015446043,-0.031024383,-0.0